Actually manually freeing each pointer is the proper way to do it in C since as Serge wrote there is no automatic destructor call in C. However you can make it manual and pretty without resorting to a dynamic stack or a garbage collector like solutions which in my opinion would usually be a huge overkill. So without further ado.

1. Name the creator function so that it is clear it allocates memory like create... or allocate... or new... and not get. Let&#39;s assume create/delete nomenclature here. So:

    `int* create_matrix(int size);`

Note I am using `int*`, not `int**`. It is more convenient, does not require you to do all the second dimension allocations, you simply allocate one array of size `n*n`. In memory this is the same space. You may however stick to 2 dimensions if you prefer.

2. Next the destructor

    `void delete_matrix(int* matrix);`

3. Now that we have some pretty syntax, we modify your operation prototypes. Instead of taking two arrays and returning a newly allocated one, operate on the first argument. Your multiplication function allocating data is not good as it is not intuitive to assume that multiplication allocates new data instead of returning it by value. So:

    `int* matmul_recursive(int* left, const int* right, int size);`

Note we will not be modifying `right`, hence the const. We will be modifying `left` hence no const. Now write your multiplication of `left` and `right` and put your results into `left`. No additional allocation means no leaks. The function should return `left` for convenience chained calls.

Note that you can add a `int* create_matrix_copy(const int* source, int size);` to clone a matrix.

Note also that you will typically not be needing the arguments of the operations after the operations. You will be interested in the resulting cumulated matrix. See this sample (using your function names):

    int* arg1 = create_matrix(n);
    int* arg2 = create_matrix(n);
    int* product1 = create_matrix(n);
    int* product2 = create_matrix(n);
    int* result = m_add(matmul_recursive(product1, arg1, n), matmul_recursive(product2, arg2, n), n);
    delete_matrix(arg1);
    delete_matrix(arg2);
    delete_matrix(product2);
    printf(&quot;%d&quot;, product1[0]);
    printf(&quot;%d&quot;, result[0]); // result == product1
    delete_matrix(product1);

Also use `const` whenever applicable i.e. you do not change the value of the argument, heplps avoid mistakes. Also consider using `unsigned int` for sizes.

Also more often then not you will probably do many operations on one matrix, hence this will be more common (like 3D transformations):

    int* result = create_matrix(n);
    int* rotate = create_matrix(n);
    int* translate = create_matrix(n);
    int* scale = create_matrix(n);
    matmul_recursive(matmul_recursive(matmul_recursive(result, rotate, n), translate, n), scale, n);
    printf(&quot;%d&quot;, result[0]);
    // Remember to delete all arguments.

In `C` you do not have the luxuries you have in `C++`, so memory de-allocation is left to you only.  If you really want to avoid de-allocation the matrices one by one you can do something like the following:

To create a `struct` that is responsible for the storage of all the addresses of the created matrices (let&#39;s call it container). 

1. So your functions will take also a pointer to this matrix container object. When get_matrix is called the address of the newly allocated matrix is added to the container. 

2. All you need to do at the end of the calculation, is to properly free the container. 

Something like the following (pseudocode below):

    int** get_matrix(int size, struct MatricesContainer* cnt){ //takes the container
        int** m = malloc(size*sizeof(int));
        for (int i=0;i&lt;size;i++){
            m[i] = malloc(size*sizeof(int));
        }
        vector_push_back(m, cnt); //push_the address in the container
        return m;
    }

    int** m_sub(int** a, int** b, int size, struct MatricesContainer* cnt) {
        int **result = get_matrix(size, cnt); //address of result is stored in cnt
        // calculate addition of a &amp; b
        return result;
    }


and use it normally and then destroying it in a function

    int heavy_calculation(...)
    {
    struct MatricesContainer* cnt
       .....
       m_copy(c_11,m_add(matmul_recursive(n/2, a,e, cnt),matmul_recursive(n/2, b, g,cnt),   n/2), n/2,cnt); 
       ...
       destroy_container(cnt);
    }

`destroy_container` loops over the vector of matrices and frees them one by one. 


Please not that as stated in the comment `get_matrix` has problems. `int** m = malloc(size*sizeof(int));` should be `int** m = malloc(size*sizeof(int*));` as you need to allocate space for pointers and not for `int`s.

